                <h2>The Chronicles of Thomas Covenant, the Unbeliever</h2>
                <p class="author">Stephen R. Donaldson</p>
                <p>The Thomas Covenant books are difficult. I would gladly recommend them to anyone, with the warning that
                they are thick. Not necessarily page-wise, but content-wise. Donaldson does very little to ease the reader
                into the baffling world of The Land. We follow Thomas Covenant, a leper in the "real" world who is
                transported to the fantastical world of The Land, a place where health can be seen and hear, and evil is
                tangible. Covenant, impotent in our world, finds that he holds great power in The Land, though he can not
                control it. This place of unreal vitality presses on his sanity as he tries to cope with the reality of
                his illness and the paradox of The Land. It is a unique blend of fantasy and psychological exploration.</p>
